China Overseas Land, Geely, Henderson: Hong Kong Stocks Preview

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-04-20T01:01:43Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-20/china-overseas-land-geely-henderson-hong-kong-stocks-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in Hong Kong trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  dropped 1.3 percent to 23,520.62. The
Hang Seng  China  Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H
shares of Chinese companies, fell 1.2 percent to 13,246.86.  Chinese banks: China told banks to conduct a new round of
stress tests on their real-estate loans to gauge the impact of a
decline in housing prices. Banks should strengthen the
management of property lending and loans to local government
financing vehicles, China Banking Regulatory Commission Chairman
 Liu Mingkang  said.  Industrial & Commercial Bank of China (601398)  Ltd. (1398 HK), the
world’s No. 1 lender by market value, fell 2 percent to HK$6.43.
 China Construction Bank Corp. (939)  (939 HK), the second-biggest,
declined 1.5 percent to HK$7.23. Bank of China Ltd. (3988 HK),
the country’s third-largest, slid 1.6 percent to HK$4.29.  China Overseas Land & Investment Ltd. (688)  (688 HK): The company,
controlled by the nation’s construction ministry, said first-
quarter property sales rose 44 percent to HK$19.8 billion ($2.55
billion) from a year earlier. The stock fell 3.6 percent to
HK$15.56.  China Shenhua Energy Co. (1088 HK): The listed unit of
China’s largest coal producer said March output rose 30 percent
to 24.6 million tons from a year earlier. The stock retreated
0.6 percent to HK$35.50.  Geely Automobile Holdings Ltd. (175)  (175 HK): Volvo Cars, the
Swedish carmaker owned by Zhejiang Geely Holding Group Co., is
considering building a second production plant in the world’s
largest car market to meet unexpected demand, according to Chief
Executive Officer  Stefan Jacoby . Geely Automobile sank 3.9
percent to HK$3.19.  Henderson Land Development Co. (12 HK): Chairman Lee Shau-
kee bought about HK$32 million worth of shares of the company on
April 13, according to a filing to the Hong Kong stock exchange.
Lee bought 576,000 shares at an average price of HK$55.911 each,
raising his stake to 66.85 percent from 66.83 percent, the
filing showed. The stock dropped 1.5 percent to HK$53.75.  Minmetals Resources Ltd. (1208)  (1208 HK): The unit of China’s
biggest metals trader said it is placing 762.6 million shares at
HK$5.10 apiece, raising gross proceeds of HK$3.89 billion. The
company has requested to resume the trading of its shares, which
last traded at HK$5.89, after being suspended on April 18.  Soho China Ltd. (410)  (410 HK): The developer said it
successfully bid 2.47 billion yuan ($379 million) to buy land
for mixed development at Hailun Station on subway line 10 in
 Shanghai . This is the company’s sixth project in Shanghai,
according to an e-mailed statement. The stock fell 3.9 percent
to HK$6.74.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in  Tokyo  at 
 knishizawa5@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
